istoriography of modern schemes for social engineering, the Holocaust, ethnic deportations, collaboration, and postwar settlements. For communist true believers, World War II was the purgatory of the revolution, the final cleansing of Soviet society of the remaining elusive "human weeds" who intruded upon socialist harmony, and it brought the polity to the brink of communism. Those ridden with doubts turned to the war as a redemption for past wrongs of the regime, while others hoped it would be the death blow to an evil enterprise. For all, it was the Armageddon of the Bolshevik Revolution. The result of Weiner's inquiry is a bold, compelling new picture of a Soviet Union both reinforced and enfeebled by the experience of total war.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aCommunismzSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xSocial aspectszSoviet Union. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zSoviet UnionxPsychological aspects. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zSoviet Union. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aAbwehr.  aAllied-occupied Germany.  aAnti-fascism.  aAntisemitism (authors).  aAntisemitism.  aBanditry.  aBattle cry.  aBattle of Moscow.  aBattle of Stalingrad.  aBolsheviks.  aCentral Committee.  aCivil war.  aCollaboration with the Axis Powers during World War II.  aCollective punishment.  aColonial war.  aCombatant.  aCommunism.  aCounter-revolutionary.  aDe-Stalinization.  aDecossackization.  aDekulakization.  aDemagogue.  aDemoralization (warfare).  aDenazification.  aDeportation.  aDestruction battalions.  aEinsatzgruppen.  aEinsatzkommando.  aGerman war crimes.  aGreat Patriotic War (term).  aGuerrilla warfare.  aHitler's Willing Executioners.  aHome front during World War II.  aImperialism.  aInsurgency.  aInvasion of Poland.  aJe